The <b>Dwarf Jay</b> (<i><b>Cyanolyca nana</b></i>) is a species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> in the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corvidae" title="Corvidae">Corvidae</a> family. It is <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endemism" title="Endemism">endemic</a> to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title="Mexico">Mexico</a>. Its natural <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitat</a> is subtropical or tropical moist <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montane_forest" title="Montane forest" class="mw-redirect">montane forests</a>. Contrary to its name, this is the smallest bird in the genus <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corvidae" title="Corvidae">Corvidae</a> at 20â€“23&nbsp;cm long and weighing 41&nbsp;g. It is threatened by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat_loss" title="Habitat loss" class="mw-redirect">habitat loss</a>.
